Definition: Two analogies that relate items to whether they are trash or treasure is given in the form "A : B. C : ?". Items marked as "trash" are considered to not have value and can be disposed, whereas those marked as "treasure" are considered valuable items that must be retained. "A : "B relates item A to whether it is trash or treasure, as specified by B. Your task is to replace the question mark (?) with either `trash` or `treasure` for the given item C, following the "A : B" relation.

Positive Examples.explanation: The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Books are associated with treasure, pillows are associated with treasure
The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Leaves are associated with trash, rings are associated with treasure
The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Bugs are associated with trash, dirt is associated with trash

Negative Examples.explanation: The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Wrappers are associated with trash, BUT babies are not associated with trash
The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Peels are associated with trash. BUT coffee is the wrong answer to the cup, since it models a containment relation.
The analogy models a trash/treasure relation. Crumbs are associated with trash, BUT dust is not associated with treasure
